In our circles there are people who are astonishing. There is a sense of, "I
wish I could be like them." There are people we do not look up to. We're
constantly measuring and communicating worth. When someone is dominating the
conversation and is uninteresting, we look away or act disinterested. We build
hierarchies based on perceived worth. However, in each of our hierarchies we
must also place ourselves. Hierarchical structures, where the most competent
have the most influence, make sense for survival or business. They don't make
sense for how one measures one's worth, because no two people have the same
affinities. In fact, some people are better in every way that society measures
someone. Adlerian psychology suggests that we should forego hierarchies and
pursue horizontal relationships with regard to personal worth. There are two
possibilities. One possibility is that this isn't practical, that we have
outdated hardware. Hardware which is constantly judging and measuring and
organizing, that we cannot escape building hierarchies. The other possibility
is that we can feel worthwhile and view others as worthwhile outside of
hierarchies.

